article.description: The host Connecticut Sun erased a 16-point second-half deficit to beat the New York Liberty 62-58 on Sunday, their latest big comeback.
article.headline: Johnson, Sales help Sun rise late
article.linkText: Sun refuses to set yet again, rallies
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. -- Connecticut is making a habit of staging comebacks.

The Sun erased a 16-point second-half deficit to beat the New York Liberty 62-58 on Sunday. They also rallied from 16 points down to beat the Sacramento Monarchs 69-67 Friday when Taj McWilliams-Franklin made a layup with 3.3 seconds left.

"I don't want it to be that way every night," Sun coach Mike Thibault said. "I'll take the win every night, but I don't want to have to rally from that far down. It's too much to expect every night."

The Sun have won three straight games after losing six of their previous eight. They are 7-1 when holding teams to less than 70 points.

Connecticut fell behind early after shooting 22.6 percent in the first half. But Shannon Johnson and Nykesha Sales sparked the Sun's second-half rally, scoring six points each over the final 3:27. 

An 18-foot jumper by Sales with 1:15 left put the Sun ahead 57-55, and her two free throws with 18.2 seconds remaining sealed the win.

"We were so bad offensively in the first half, I figured eventually the shots would have to go in," Thibault said. "I decided to go with a smaller lineup in the second half to see if we could jump-start our offense. It kind of got us going."

Sales finished with 14 points and became the 21st player in WNBA history to reach 2,000 career points. Adrienne Johnson added eight points and six rebounds off the bench.

Tari Phillips had 18 points and 10 rebounds to lead the Liberty. Vickie Johnson had 12 points, and Crystal Robinson added 11.

McWilliams-Franklin was the only Sun starter with a field goal in the first half as Connecticut fell behind early. The Sun made just three of their first 20 shots and finished the half 7-for-31.

New York led 32-20 at the break. It was the lowest field-goal percentage and the lowest point total by the Sun in any half this season.

The Liberty expanded their lead to 45-29 on Johnson's reverse layup with 12:39 left in the game and led by as many as 12 points with 6:25 left.

New York then went into a shooting slump, missing 13 of its final 15 field-goal attempts. The Liberty shot just 8-for-29 (27.6 percent) in the second half.

"We definitely had our opportunities," New York coach Richie Adubato said. "I can't fault our defense, it was our offense tonight. Shots that we normally make just didn't go down. I give Connecticut a tremendous amount of credit because they had the mental toughness to stay in the game even though they were down."

The Liberty did not have the same performance as they did last Tuesday against the Sun at Madison Square Garden, where they shot 62 percent in a 90-64 win.

"They embarrassed us in New York," McWilliams-Franklin said. "Right after that, we talked to each other and said, `Look, even though we had back-to-back against the Liberty and Cleveland, we can't give up any more games. We can't be embarrassed.'

"We just buckled down. That first half was so atrocious that we couldn't do anything but play better in the second half. We worked through it and got the win."
